<br>
I see a lot of people bashing those who are "flaming Kendrick".  I don't, however, see anyone actually flaming him.  I do see a LOT of rogues that you guys have trusted for information in the past putting up valid points, concerns, and fears about this.  And in return, I see a lot of you people with your lips all over kendrick's arse, and feet on ours.<br>
<br>
I also see a lot of people saying "but hey, Verant just wants to lower our damage output, blah blah blah..".  Do you even bother to read?  Verant was FINE with evade when the hate list was 8-16 (I'd guess 16, although it has never been released, this was simply from my experience with damage in multiple group raids) people long (and it was like this for a LONG time.  It used to be that wizards and druids were the sole determination of who got xp in the planes.).<br>
<br>
The reason that it needs to be changed now is that with the hate list at ~128, is that a rogue drops SO far down the list that people who used to get pushed off before with melee damage (casters, etc) will now pickup agro if a rogue evades even once during the latter half of an epic Velious battle.<br>
<br>
The reason is NOT that "rogues do to much damage, and we wanna nerf em".  Unless Kendrick is lying to us rogues now.  In which case, @#%$ save us all.<br>
<br>
The problem with Velious is that rogues drop to the end of the hate list.  Failures on evade before would hurt us a lot more than they do in Velious.  Imagine the following scenario:<br>
<br>
5 warriors, 2 paladins, 2 sks, 3 rangers, 3 rogues, 4 clerics, 3 wizzies, 2 enchanters, 2 shamen, 2 magicians, 2 druids all level 60, all with epics on a raid (assumed fully buffed).<br>
<br>
Let's assume for a second that the old hate list was 12 players long. The way the hate list builds, within the first 20 seconds of the fight (assuming that the rogues don't evade within that period of time), you would see the hate list in this order:<br>
<br>
2 rogues<br>
2 shamen (malo/slow)<br>
1 enchanter (tash)<br>
3 warriors<br>
3 rangers<br>
1 sk<br>
-------old hate list cut---------<br>
2 paladins<br>
3 wizzies/2 druids/2 magicians (1 nuke each)<br>
1 enchanter (no spells cast)<br>
4 clerics (0-1 heal each)<br>
<br>
What does this show? rogues at the top of the list pre evade.  What about the paladins, wizzies, druids, magicians, enchanter, and clerics?  They're not on the hate list.  It's [the hate list is] so small that they have been "kicked" off the list, in essence, the mob forgets them because others have done more damage, or cast more debhilitating debuffs on it.  So, when a rogue evades, and 5 seconds after the evade is done, the hate list looks like this:<br>
<br>
3 warriors<br>
3 rangers<br>
1 sk<br>
2 paladins (kicked the shamen/enchanters from the hate list)<br>
1 cleric (just healed)<br>
2 rogues (evaded)<br>
-------old hate list cut---------<br>
2 shamen (malo/slow) (kicked off the list)<br>
1 enchanter (tash) (kicked off the list)<br>
3 wizzies/2 druids/2 magicians (1 nuke each)<br>
1 enchanter (no spells cast)<br>
3 clerics (0-1 heal each)<br>
<br>
Now, what is significant about this?  Well, for starters, the rogues aren't all the way at the end.  Why? Well, let's take a quick look a little deeper.<br>
<br>
The hate list is (in this example), 12 people long.  Those who have been kicked from the list now have 0 hate accumulated.  When a rogue evades, he/she is returned to 120 hate. Thus, still remaining on the list, but at 120 on the hate list, are lower than either paladin, or the cleric who just healed (a 400 point addition on the hate list).  Within a brief period of time (perhaps 20 seconds), they will surpass both paladins, they will pop back up on the hate list again.  This meant that rogues had to evade early and often, and they'd always be somewhere significant on the hate list.  If a warrior or main tank went down, it was always likely that a rogue would get beat on next.<br>
<br>
Now let's look at what Velious did.  imagine the same group within the same 20 seconds (let's say they're fighting a random WW named dragon):<br>
<br>
2 rogues<br>
2 shamen (malo/slow)<br>
1 enchanter (tash)<br>
3 warriors<br>
3 rangers<br>
1 sk<br>
2 paladins<br>
3 wizzies/2 druids/2 magicians (1 nuke each)<br>
1 enchanter (no spells cast)<br>
4 clerics (0-1 heal each)<br>
...60 more hate list spots to be filled...<br>
---------End of the hate list--------<br>
<br>
Again, that was pre evade on the rogues, in the first 10-20 seconds of the combat.<br>
<br>
Now, let's say the rogues evade.  Now how does the list look?<br>
<br>
3 warriors<br>
3 rangers<br>
1 sk<br>
2 paladins<br>
3 wizzies/2 druids/2 magicians (1 nuke each)<br>
2 shamen (malo/slow)<br>
1 enchanter (tash)<br>
1 enchanter (no spells cast)<br>
4 clerics (0-1 heal each)<br>
2 rogues (evaded)<br>
...60 more spots on the hate list...<br>
------------end of the hate list------------<br>
<br>
What's different here?  The rogues are at the VERY bottom of the list.  Below cumulated heals, nukes, debuffs, buffs, whatever.  They will NOT be hit ANYTIME in the near future.  Hell, at this point, they could stop attacking, go wander off somewhere, sit down, do whatever the hell they wanted to, and the mob would NOT pay attention to them until EVERYONE else was dead.<br>
<br>
THIS is what Verant didn't forsee.  But the problem is the way in which they're going about trying to fix it.  The problem is not really within single groups, as rogues will always jump up on the list very quickly in single groups, so I'm not understanding why they're looking at changing it, based around SINGLE groups.  Single groups would remain the same as they always did if rogues were moved down to the 12th-13th spots on the hate list.  The problem clearly only comes when dealing with large-scale raids, where the rogues put themselves SO far down on the hate lists that they will NEVER be hit.  But in these environments, a rogue can climb so quickly to the top of the hate list, that putting us 10-12 down on the hate list would have the same effect that putting us at the bottom did, pre-velious.<br>
<br>
I hope I make some amount of sense, and I hope you didn't just glaze over this, with merely passing interest.  This is how it works.  This is why it had to change.  And foremost, this is what should be done to fix it, rather than the extreme measures which Kendrick has listed for us here.<br>
